Part I - Exploratory analysis of the Prosper Loan Data¶

by Harnex Kakandelwa¶

Introduction¶

This dataset contains customers' loan data from the company, Prosper. The dataset covers over 100,000 loans and has information related to the listing, loan amount, number of investors, interest rate, current loan status, borrower's employment status, income and so on. More information about the dataset can be found here.

Preliminary Wrangling¶

In [1]:
# import all packages and set plots to be embedded inline
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

%matplotlib inline
In [2]:
# Load the data
loan_df = pd.read_csv('prosperLoanData.csv')

Although the above result shows that there are no duplicates, the dataframe has duplicate loans (that is, loans with the same loan number/listing number/listing keys).

In [10]:

Out[12]:
(1698, 81)

Since there are loans with duplicate loan numbers/listing numbers/listing keys, I want to see what columns have different information for such loans. This will be done using two custom functions has_same_elements() and not_duplicated().

In [13]:
def has_same_elements(data_list):
    """
    Check if all the elements of a list are the same.
    
    Parameters
    ----------
    data_list: list
    
    Returns
    -------
    bool: True if all the elements are the same and 
    False otherwise
    
    """
    return len(set(data_list)) == 1
In [14]:
def not_duplicated(data, key_column):
    '''
    Return columns where rows with duplicate values in other columns 
    are not duplicated.
    
    In certain instances, a dataframe has rows with duplicate values 
    across some columns but not all the columns. This function finds 
    the columns where the rows do not have duplicate values.
    
    This can help in deciding whether to retain or drop rows with 
    duplicates even if the duplicates are not across all the columns.
    
    Parameters
    ----------
    data: pandas dataframe
    
    key_column: str
                Name of the key column with duplicates
                
    Returns
    -------
    dict
        A dictionary with the duplicate row items as keys and the 
        columns without duplicates as values
    
    '''
    
    # Get the columns of the dataframe except the key column
    cols = list(data.columns)
    cols.remove(key_column)
    
    # Create an empty dictionary to hold the duplicate element 
    # and the columns for which the row is not duplicated
    results_dict = {}
    
    # Create a temporal dataframe with the duplicates
    temporal_duplicates_df = data.query(f'{key_column}.duplicated(keep=False)')
    
    # Loop through the dataframe and create a temporal dataframe 
    # for each of the duplicate elements in the key column
    for element in list(temporal_duplicates_df[key_column].unique()):
        temp_df = temporal_duplicates_df[temporal_duplicates_df[key_column]==element]
        
        # Create an empty list to hold the columns which do not
        # have duplicates
        without_duplicates = []
        
        # Loop through the temp dataframe
        for c in cols:
            if has_same_elements(list(temp_df[c].values)):
                pass
            else:
                without_duplicates.append(c)
                
        # Add the results to the results dictionary
        if len(without_duplicates) == 0:
            pass
        else:
            results_dict[element] = without_duplicates

    
    return results_dict

For loans with duplicate loan numbers, columns that have different information include the

  • 'ProsperScore'
  • 'TotalProsperLoans'
  • 'TotalProsperPaymentsBilled'
  • 'OnTimeProsperPayments'
  • 'ProsperPaymentsLessThanOneMonthLate'
  • 'ProsperPaymentsOneMonthPlusLate'
  • 'ProsperPrincipalBorrowed'
  • 'ProsperPrincipalOutstanding'
  • 'ScorexChangeAtTimeOfListing'
  • 'LoanFirstDefaultedCycleNumber'.

However, all these columns seem to have different information because they have NaN's except the 'ProsperScore' column. In other words, the significant differences are only in the 'ProsperScore' column.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The original dataset has 113937 loans and 81 features. There is a good mix of numeric and non numeric variables.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

In this investigation, my interest is to figure out what loan and borrower characteristics are associated with a high number of investors. Are there features in the data that would best predict the likelihood of investors funding a loan? My main variable of interest is therefore the number of investors that fund the loan.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

My expectation is that variables such as the estimated return, loan amount, loan term, and risk score will have the strongest effect on the number of investors that fund a loan. Other features such as employment status, monthly income (including whether the income is verifiable or not), home ownership, and whether the loan listing is associated with a new or old customer will also have a minor influence on the number of investors.

Data Cleaning¶

Before going in further exploration and analysis, I will do some prelininary cleaning to resolve some tidiness and quality issues in the data. The issues to be dealt with in this round of cleaning include the following:

  1. Some loans have a prosper score that is greater than 10
  2. The dataframe has different prosper scores for loans with the same loan number/listing number/listing keys
  3. Information about whether a borrower is new or old is in different columns
  4. ListingCreationDate and LoanOriginationDate are in wrong data type
  5. EmploymentStatus has both "employed" and "full time"
In [17]:
# Make a copy of the dataframe
loan_df_clean = loan_df.copy()

Issue #1: Some loans have a prosper score that is greater than 10¶

Define:¶

According to the variable definitions (available here), 'ProsperScore' is a custom risk score built using historical Prosper data. The score ranges from 1-10, with 10 being the best, or lowest risk score. In this context, therefore, a prosper score that is greater than 10 is invalid. To resolve this issue, all the scores that are greater than 10 will be treated as null.

Code¶

In [18]:
for score in loan_df_clean.ProsperScore:
    if score > 10:
        loan_df_clean.at[loan_df_clean[loan_df_clean['ProsperScore']==score].index[0], 'ProsperScore'] = np.NaN

Test¶

In [19]:
loan_df_clean[loan_df_clean['ProsperScore'] > 10].shape
Out[19]:
(0, 81)

Issue #2: The dataframe has different prosper scores for the same loans (that is, loans with the same loan number/listing number/listing keys)¶

Define:¶

Get the average prosper score for loans that have different scores and store in a new column

Code¶

In [20]:
# Function to compute mean of specified column for duplicate rows 
def get_mean_for_duplicates(data, duplicate_value, column_with_duplicates, column_to_compute):
    return data[data[column_with_duplicates]==duplicate_value][column_to_compute].mean()
In [21]:
duplicated_loan_numbers = list(loan_df_clean.query('LoanNumber.duplicated(keep=False)')['LoanNumber'].unique())
average_prosper_score_for_duplicates = []

# Loop through the loan numbers in the dataframe and compute 
# the mean for the duplicates
for loan_number in loan_df_clean.LoanNumber:
    if loan_number in duplicated_loan_numbers:
        average_prosper_score_for_duplicates.append(get_mean_for_duplicates(loan_df_clean, loan_number, 'LoanNumber', 'ProsperScore'))
    else:
        average_prosper_score_for_duplicates.append(loan_df_clean.at[loan_df_clean[loan_df_clean['LoanNumber']==loan_number].index[0],'ProsperScore'])
        
# Create a new column for prosper score in the dataframe
# The new column is conveniently named "RiskScore"
loan_df_clean.loc[:, 'RiskScore'] = average_prosper_score_for_duplicates
In [22]:
# Drop the rows with duplicate loans
loan_df_clean.drop_duplicates(subset=['LoanNumber', 'ListingNumber', 'ListingKey'], inplace=True)
In [23]:
# Drop the original ProsperScore column
loan_df_clean.drop(columns='ProsperScore', inplace=True)

Issue #3: Information about whether a borrower is new or old is in different columns¶

Define¶

Create a new column that shows whether a borrower is new or old (had prior loans)

There are a number of columns from which information on whether the borrower had prior loans at the time the listing was created can be inferred, for example, the TotalProsperLoans, OnTimeProsperPayments, TotalProsperPaymentsBilled, ProsperPrincipalBorrowed and so on. To uniquely identify whether a borrower had prior loans or not, will make use of the MemberKey column.

Code¶

In [27]:
# Create an empty list to hold the borrower type
# This will be used to create the new column
borrower_type_list = []

duplicated_member_keys = loan_df.query('MemberKey.duplicated(keep=False)')['MemberKey'].unique()

for member in loan_df_clean.MemberKey:
    if member in duplicated_member_keys:
        borrower_type_list.append("Old")
    else:
        borrower_type_list.append("New")
        
loan_df_clean.loc[:, 'BorrowerType'] = borrower_type_list

Some useful custom functions¶

In [35]:
# Function for labelling plots
def set_plot_labels(plot_title=None, x_label=None, y_label=None, title_fontsize = 14, axis_fontsize = 13):
    plt.title(plot_title, fontsize=title_fontsize)
    plt.xlabel(x_label, fontsize=axis_fontsize)
    plt.ylabel(y_label, fontsize=axis_fontsize)
In [36]:
# Function to create a histogram with custom defined bins
def custom_hist(data, column, left_most, bin_width):
    bins = np.arange(left_most, data[column].max()+bin_width, bin_width)
    plt.hist(data=data, x=column, bins=bins)
In [37]:
# Function to define how categories should be ordered 
# in a bar chart if the column is of type string
def category_order(data, column, order='desc', order_list=None):
    sorted_list = None
    if order == 'desc':
        sorted_list = list(data[column].value_counts().sort_values(ascending=False).index)
    elif order == 'asc':
        sorted_list = list(data[column].value_counts().sort_values().index)
    elif order == 'custom':
        try:
            if len(order_list) == len(list(data[column].value_counts().index)):
                sorted_list = order_list
            else:
                print("Length of custom list does not match the categories in the data")
        except (TypeError, ValueError, IndexError) as err:
            print("Not a valid custom list:", err)
            
    return sorted_list

Understanding the main variable of interest¶

How is the number of investors distributed?¶

In [39]:
custom_hist(data=master_loan_df, column='Investors', left_most=0, bin_width=50)
set_plot_labels(plot_title="Distribution of number of investors", x_label="Investors", y_label=common_loan_axis_title);

The data suggests that for most of the loans, the number of investors is from 1 to 100. Only in a few cases, do we have more than 500 investors funding a loan. In extremely few cases, we have more than 900 investors. Although these are outliers in the data, I will leave them for now because I want to find out what type of loans are associated with such high numbers of investors.

Next, will look at some of the features that will help in my investigation. This will involve the exploration of the characteristics of the loans (for example, loan amount, loan term, interest rate etc) and an exploration of the characteristics of the borrowers for example employment status, income, borrower type etc.

Understanding Prosper's Loans¶

What is the distribution of the loan amounts?¶

In [40]:
custom_hist(data=master_loan_df, column='LoanOriginalAmount', left_most=0, bin_width=5000)
set_plot_labels(plot_title='Distribution of loan amount', y_label=common_loan_axis_title, x_label='Loan Amount ($)');

Most of the loans gotten by Prosper's borrowers do not exceed 10000 dollars. There are, however, a few loans that are between 30000 and 35000 dollars.

What loan terms are available?¶

In [41]:
order = category_order(master_loan_df, 'Term', order='custom', order_list=[12,36,60])
sns.countplot(data=master_loan_df, x='Term', order=order, color=default_color)
set_plot_labels(plot_title='Loan Tenure', y_label=common_loan_axis_title, x_label='Term (in months)');

The loan terms available are 12, 36 and 60 months. Most of the loans in the data have a loan term of 36 months.

The interest rate on most of the loans is between 10% and 20%. There are also a few loans with interest rate of almost 50%. Furthermore, the expected return on most of the loans is between 5% and 15%.

What risk level is associated with most of the loans?¶

For this, I have decided to segment the risk score into bins that classify a score as either high risk, moderate risk or low risk. Risk scores from 1 to 4.5 (4.5 inclusive) are classified as "High", 4.5 to 9 (9 inclusive) as "Moderate" and above 9 as "Low".

In [48]:
def create_bins(data, intervals, labels, include_lower_limit=False):
    return pd.cut(data, intervals, labels = labels, include_lowest=include_lower_limit)
In [49]:
# use the create_bins function to create a column "RiskLevel" 
# that classifies the risk scores
master_loan_df.loc[:,'RiskLevel'] = create_bins(data=master_loan_df.RiskScore, intervals=[1,4.5,9,10], labels=['High', 'Moderate', 'Low'], include_lower_limit=True)
In [50]:
# Change the data type of the "RiskLevel" column
cat_dtype = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(categories=['Low','Moderate','High'], ordered=True)
master_loan_df['RiskLevel'] = master_loan_df['RiskLevel'].astype(cat_dtype)

master_loan_df.RiskLevel.dtype
Out[50]:
CategoricalDtype(categories=['Low', 'Moderate', 'High'], ordered=True)
In [51]:
sns.countplot(data=master_loan_df, x='RiskLevel', color=default_color)
set_plot_labels(plot_title='What risk levels are associated with the loans?', x_label='Risk Level', y_label=common_loan_axis_title);

Based on Prosper's custom risk score, the majority of loans are associated with borrowers whose risk level can be said to be moderate followed by loans for borrowers in the high risk category. A very small number of loans are associated with low risk borrowers.

The number of investors that fund most of the loans is between 0 and 100. In extremely few cases, we have more than 900 investors funding a loan. Although these are outliers in the data, I have left them for now because it will be interesting to find out what type of loans are associated with such high numbers of investors.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

The StatedMonthlyIncome variable has a few extremely large values, in excess of 50000 dollars, with one data point showing a value greater than one million dollars. Although these extreme values distort the general distribution of the stated monthly income, I have not dealt with them at this point as I want to see how the variable interacts with other features in the next stage of the exploration.

Bivariate Exploration¶

I will also explore some relationships among the supporting features whenever it is necessary to answer certain questions.

Does loan term influence investors?¶

In [54]:
sns.boxplot(data=master_loan_df, y='Investors', x='Term', color=default_color)
set_plot_labels(plot_title='Investors and loan term', x_label='Term (in months)', y_label=common_investor_axis_title);

Regardless of term, most of the loans have less than 200 investors. Loans that run for 36 months seem to have a high number of investors, going as high as 1200 although this could be because of the high number of loans with a term of 36 months in the data.

Based on the median, however, 12 and 36 months loans have a similar number of investors while 60 months loans have the lowest median number of investors. To see this clearly, I have plotted the median number of investors in each term on a bar chart (shown below). I have opted to use the median instead of the mean due to the presence of outliers that could otherwise influence the mean.

In [55]:

The bar chart clearly shows that although loans with a term of 36 months have a higher median number of investors, loans that run for 12 months equally have a considerable number of investors. Infact, both 12 and 36 months loans have a median number of investors close to 50. Only 60 months loans have a median number of investors that is less than 20.

Is there a relationship between the number of investors and both interest rate (borrower rate) and estimated return?¶

In [56]:

The relationships between the number of investors and interest rate and the number of investors and estimated return are similar. This is expected because estimated return is based on interest rate. A positive relationship between the two variables can be seen in the scatter plot below.

In [57]:
plt.scatter(data=master_loan_df, x='BorrowerRate', y='EstimatedReturn')
set_plot_labels(plot_title="Relationship between interest rate and estimated return", x_label="Interest Rate", y_label='Estimated return');

All in all, there doesn't seem to be a relationship between the borrower's interest rate and the number of investors. Its actually unusual that loans with high interest rates, for example, close to 50% are associated with very few investors while loans with interest rates between 10% and 30% seem to be associated with a very high number of investors. Similarly, loans with a high estimated return (close to 30%) seem to be associated with very few investors while loans with an estimated return of between 5% and 20% seem to attract more investors. Could it be that low interest rates signify low risk and therefore more attractive to investors?

To see this clearly, I want to check if there is a relationship between interest rate and risk level.

In [58]:
sns.violinplot(data=master_loan_df, x='RiskLevel', y='BorrowerRate')
set_plot_labels('Risk Level and Interest Rate', 'Risk Level', 'Interest Rate');

The data seems to suggest that indeed most of the loans that are associated with borrowers that are in the low risk category have lower interest rates than loans for moderate and high risk borrowers. Even in terms of the median, loans associated with borrowers in the high risk category have the highest median interest rate while loans for low risk borrowers have the lowest. This could explain why loans with relatively low interest rates and thus estimated return seem to be associated with a high number of investors. Perhaps most investors are risk averse?

The first and third checks suggest to me that the extremely large stated monthly income values may have been a result of errors in the data. In analyzing monthly income, therefore, I will not consider these outliers (in this case, the values that are greater than 50000 dollars). Furthermore, I will only consider income values that are verifiable.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

The number of investors funding a loan did not show most of the expected relationships. Specifically, interest rate, estimated return, loan term, loan amount and stated monthly income did not show any correlation with the number of investors. For loan amount and stated monthly income, no relationship was observed even after plotting the features on a log scale.

However, it was interesting that loans with high interest rates and thus estimated return were associated with very few investors while loans with relatively low interest rates and estimated return seemed to have a very high number of investors. In the next section, will explore if there are other variables in the data that support this.

The other variables showed striking differences when looked at in terms of the distribution of the data points and through a summary statistic. The distribution of investors for each employment status, for example, showed that loans for full-time and self-employed borrowers had the highest number of investors. In terms of the median, however, loans for retired and part-time borrowers had a higher median number of investors than loans for full-time and self-employed borrowers. A similar observation was made for loan term. One of the reasons for this is the presence of outliers in the data. In the next section, will explore if there are other explantions for this.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

Since loans with relatively low interest rate and estimated return were associated with a high number of investors, I wanted to check whether the low interest rates would signify low risk thus making the loans more attractive to investors. To do this, I explored the relationship between risk level and interest rate. The results showed that most of the loans that were associated with borrowers in the low or moderate risk category had lower interest rates than loans for borrowers in the high risk category. These preliminary results seem to have supported the proposition that relatively low interest rates could signify low risk thus making such loans more attractive to investors.

Multivariate Exploration¶

In the previous section, the data seemed to support the proposition that relatively low interest rates could signify relatively low risk, thus making loans with low interest rates more attractive to a good number of investors. In this section, therefore, I want to explore what other loan characteristics are associated with low risk. How do they affect the number of investors funding a loan? Similarly, the data showed that loans with a high estimated return were associated with very few investors while loans with a relatively low estimated return seemed to have a very high number of investors. So I want to explore whether this occurrence is supported by other variables.

The results of the previous section also showed that loans associated with part-time or retired borrowers had a higher median number of investors than those for full-time or self-employed borrowers. This was despite the fact that loans for full-time and self-employed borrowers had the highest number of investors in absolute terms. Therefore, I want to explore whether this was an isolated case (purely due to the presence of outliers) or is supported by other variables in the data.

Context¶

In this section, I want to only work with loans that are associated with verifiable income and do not have outliers in stated monthly income (in this case, values exceeding $ 50000). This approach is supported by the checks that I carried out in the previous section on the StatedMonthlyIncome column, which suggested that the extremely large monthly income values may have been a result of errors in the data.

In [72]:
# Create a copy of the master_loan_df
final_loan_df = master_loan_df.copy()
In [73]:
# Drop the rows that have unverified income and 
# stated monthly income greater than $ 50000
rows_to_drop = final_loan_df.query('StatedMonthlyIncome > 50000 & IncomeVerifiable == "No"').index
final_loan_df.drop(rows_to_drop, inplace=True)

Investors and estimated return in the context of other variables¶

What loan amounts have an estimated return that is associated with a high number of investors?¶

In [74]:

set_plot_labels(plot_title="Relationship between investors, loan amount and estimated return", x_label="Estimated Return", y_label=common_investor_axis_title);

As earlier observed, loans with a high estimated return (close to 30%) seem to be associated with very few investors while loans with an estimated return of between 5% and 20% seem to attract more investors. Loans with an estimated return of about 10% have the highest number of investors. These loans have loan amounts between 20000 and 30000 dollars. One thing worth noting about most of the loans with an estimated return close to 30% but small number of investors is that the loan amounts are also relatively smaller (less than 10000 dollars). Looks like loan amount also does have an influence on investors.

It seems loan term does not have that much influence on estimated return and number of investors.

Investors and risk level in the context of other variables¶

What loan terms are associated with a low risk level and high number of investors?¶

Across all loan terms, loans associated with borrowers who can be categorized as low risk have the highest median number of investors followed by loans for moderate risk borrowers. This can clearly be seen in the barplot of the median number of investors below. For loans associated with moderate and high risk borrowers, the median number of investors seems to be decreasing as the loan term increases. This suggests that investors are less likely to fund loans associated with risky borrowers if the term is long, for example, 36 months or more.

Are most loans associated with old borrowers in the low risk category compared to new ones?¶

In the previous section, the data showed that investors are more likely to fund loans for old (or existing) borrowers than new ones. I'm interested in finding out if most of the loans associated with old borrowers are also in the low risk category.

In [78]:
sns.barplot(data=final_loan_df, x='BorrowerType', y='Investors', hue='RiskLevel', estimator=np.median, ci=None)
set_plot_labels(plot_title="Investors, borrower type and risk level", x_label="Borrower Type", y_label='Median number of investors');

Loans associated with low risk borrowers have a similar median number of investors for both old and new borrowers. This seems to suggest that borrowers who are categorized as low risk are more likely to have their loans funded regardless of whether they are getting a loan for the first time or not.

What is the employment status associated with low risk?¶

The results of the previous section also showed that loans associated with part-time or retired borrowers had a higher median number of investors than those for full-time or self-employed borrowers. This was despite the fact that loans for full-time and self-employed borrowers had the highest number of investors in absolute terms. So how does employment status relate to risk level? Are part-time or retired borrowers considered low risk?

For this, I will concentrate only on those self-employed, full-time, part-time and retired.

In [79]:
fg = sns.catplot(data=final_loan_df[final_loan_df['EmploymentStatus'].isin(['Self-employed', 'Full-time', 'Part-time', 'Retired'])], 
            x='RiskLevel', y='Investors', kind='bar', col='EmploymentStatus', aspect=0.5, estimator=np.median, ci=None,
           orient='v', palette=sns.color_palette('colorblind'))

fg.set(xlabel="Risk Level", ylabel="Median number of investors");

The data shows that loans associated with full-time and low risk borrowers have the highest median number of investors. Interestly, however, is how loans associated with retired and part-time borrowers have a higher median number of investors across almost all the risk levels than loans associated with self-employed borrowers and even full-time borrowers (in the case of moderate and high risk). This seems consistent with the results in the previous section that showed that loans associated with part-time or retired borrowers had a higher median number of investors than those for full-time or self-employed borrowers.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

In this section I looked at how the association between number of investors and estimated return and number of investors and risk level were influenced by other variables. In terms of investors and estimated return, the data showed that most of the loans with a very high estimated return had a small loan amount and number of investors. This seemed to suggest that loan amount had an influence on the level of the estimated return that investors would be willing to fund.

In terms of investors and risk level, the results showed that loans associated with low risk customers had the highest median number of investors across the features investigated, which included loan term, borrower type and employment status.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

The interaction between risk level and employment status strengthed the initial finding that loans associated with part-time or retired borrowers had a higher median number of investors than those for full-time or self-employed borrowers. This was despite the fact that loans for full-time and self-employed borrowers had the highest number of investors in absolute terms and the highest median monthly income.

Conclusions¶

Firstly, the results show that loans with high interest rates and thus estimated return are associated with very few investors while loans with relatively low interest rates and estimated return seem to have a very high number of investors. This seems to support the proposition that relatively low interest rates could signify low risk thus making such loans more attractive to investors. Delving deep into this, the data suggests that loans associated with borrowers that can be classified as low risk are indeed likely to be funded by investors regardless of the loan term, employment status, and whether the borrower is new or old. The results also suggest that loan amount has an influence on the level of estimated return at which lenders are more likely to fund a loan.

These results were arrived at after creating a new column RiskLevel that grouped the different custom risk scores into bins of low risk, moderate risk and high risk. The interaction between risk level and the number of investors was then considered in the context of the other variables.
